    "abstractNote": "What did Syriac Christians focus on when they wrote about and against Islam? What aspects of Islam did they write about when they wanted to show that Islam was not the true religion? Did their approach to Islam change over time? This article discusses six Syriac responses to Islam (7th-13th c.) in an attempt to answer these questions: The Disputation of John Sedra and the Emir, The Disputation between a Muslim and a Monk of B\u0113t \u1e24\u0101l\u0113, The Legend of Sergius Ba\u1e25\u012br\u0101, Patriarch Timothy I\u2019s Disputation with the Caliph al-Mahd\u012b, Dionysius bar \u1e62al\u012bb\u012b\u2019s Disputation against the Nation of the Arabs and Barhebraeus\u2019 Candelabrum sanctuarii. In each case I detect references to contemporary debates among Muslims and I discuss how allusions to intra-Muslim disagreement reinforce the claim that Islam cannot rival Christianity.",
